<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-09-05T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-09-05T16:00:00-05:00" n="329" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.77/256: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-09-05T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">September 5,
                                        1923—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>109. Your No. 121, August 24, 1 p.m.<note n="42" xml:id="d329fn42">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <p>Cable from American Embassy, Paris,<note n="42" xml:id="d329fn43">Not
                                printed.</note> states that Farnham considers authorization
                            sufficient for negotiations with French bondholders, but that it will be
                            necessary for Government of Haiti definitely to authorize issue of the
                            bonds required in this transaction.</p>
                        <p>Department assumes that law authorizing C bonds will be passed
                            subsequently.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>